===Etymology 1===
{{bor|en|fr|portemanteau||coat stand}}, from {{m|fr|porte||carry}} + {{m|fr|manteau||coat}}.

====Noun====
{{en-noun|s|portmanteaux}}

# A large [[travel]]ling [[case]] usually made of [[leather]], and opening into two equal sections.
#* {{quote-book|lang=en|year=1667|author=Charles Croke|title=Fortune's Uncertainty|passage=Rodolphus therefore finding such an earnest Invitation, embrac'd it with thanks, and with his Servant and '''Portmanteau''', went to Don Juan's; where they first found good Stabling for their Horses, and afterwards as good Provision for themselves.}}
#* {{quote-book|lang=en|year=1859|author=Charles Dickens|title=The Haunted House|passage=He brought down with him to our haunted house a little cask of salt beef; for, he is always convinced that all salt beef not of his own pickling, is mere carrion, and invariably, when he goes to London, packs a piece in his '''portmanteau'''.}}
# {{lb|en|Australia|dated}} A [[schoolbag]]; often shortened to ''port'' or ''school port''
# {{lb|en|archaic}} A [[hook]] on which to [[hang]] [[clothing]].

