==English==
{{slim-wikipedia|Pie (disambiguation)}}
[[Image:Lemon Meringue Pie 1.jpg|thumb|Unsliced lemon meringue pie.]]

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|US|UK}} {{enPR|pƒ´}}, {{IPA|/pa…™/|lang=en}}
* {{audio|en-us-pie.ogg|Audio (US)|lang=en}}
* {{audio|en-au-pie.ogg|Audio (AU)|lang=en}}
* {{homophones|pi|œÄ|lang=en}}
* {{rhymes|a…™|lang=en}}

===Etymology 1===
From {{inh|en|enm|pye}}, {{m|enm|pie}}, probably from {{bor|en|la|pƒ´ca||magpie, jay}} (from the idea of the many ingredients put into pies likened to the tendency of magpies to bring a variety of objects back to their nests).

====Noun====
{{en-noun|~}}

# A type of [[pastry]] that consists of an outer crust and a [[filling]].
#: {{ux|en|The family had steak and kidney '''pie''' for dinner and cherry '''pie''' for dessert.}}
# Any of various other, non-pastry dishes that maintain the general concept of a shell with a filling.
#: {{ux|en|Shepherd's '''pie''' is made of mince covered with mashed potato.}}
# {{lb|en|Northeastern US}} [[pizza|Pizza]].
# {{lb|en|figuratively}} The [[whole]] of a wealth or [[resource]], to be divided in parts.
#* {{quote-journal|lang=en|passage=It is easier to get along when everyone, more or less, is getting ahead. But when the '''pie''' is shrinking, social groups are more likely to turn on each other.|author=[[w:Evan Thomas|Evan Thomas]]|url=http://www.newsweek.com/2010/12/04/the-deepest-dangers-facing-the-united-states.html|date=2010-12-04|title=Why It‚Äôs Time to Worry|work=Newsweek}}
# {{lb|en|letterpress}} A disorderly mess of spilt [[type]].
# {{lb|en|cricket}} An especially badly [[bowl]]ed ball.
# {{lb|en|pejorative}} a [[gluttonous]] person.
# A [[pie chart]].
#* {{quote-book|lang=en|year=1986|author=Carolyn Sorensen, Henry J. Stock|title=Department of Education Computer Graphics Guide|page=8|passage='''Pies''' are best for comparing the components of only one or two totals.}}
# {{lb|en|slang}} The [[vulva]].
#* {{quote-book|lang=en|year=1981|author=William Kotzwinkle|title=Jack in the Box|passage="Yeah, take it off!" "SHOW US YOUR '''PIE'''!" The brunette opened the catch on her G-string and let the sequinned cloth slip down, teasing them with it.}}
#* {{quote-book|lang=en|year=2010|author=W. A. Moltinghorne|title=Magnolia Park|page=238|passage=Yeah, some guys like to eat the old hairy '''pie'''. Women, too, or so I've heard.}}

