===Etymology 2===
{{inh|en|enm|crowen}}, from {{inh|en|ang|crƒÅwan}} (past tense {{m|ang|crƒìow}}, past participle {{m|ang|crƒÅwen}}), from {{inh|en|gem-pro|*krƒìanƒÖ}} (compare Dutch {{m|nl|kraaien}}, German {{m|de|kr√§hen}}), from {{inh|en|ine-pro|*greh‚ÇÇ-}} ‚Äòto caw, croak‚Äô (compare Lithuanian {{m|lt|gr√≥ti}}, Russian {{m|ru|–≥—Ä–∞ÃÅ—è—Ç—å}}). Related to {{m|en|croak}}.

====Verb====
{{en-verb|crows|crowing|crowed|past2=crew|past2_qual=UK|crowed|past_ptc2=crown|past_ptc2_qual=archaic}}

# To make the [[shrill]] [[sound]] characteristic of a rooster; to make a sound in this manner, either in joy, gaiety, or defiance.
#* {{RQ:Shakespeare Hamlet|I|ii|passage=The morning cock '''crew''' loud.}}
#* {{quote-song|lang=en|year=1962|author={{w|Bob Dylan}}|title={{w|Don't Think Twice, It's All Right}}|passage=When your rooster '''crows''' at the break o' dawn / Look out your window and I'll be gone.|album=The Freewheelin' Bob Dylan}}
# To [[shout]] in exultation or defiance; to [[brag]].
#: {{syn|en|brag}}
#* {{quote-web
|lang=en
|date=2017-09-27
|author=Julianne Tveten
|title=Zucktown, USA
|work=The Baffler
|url=https://thebaffler.com/latest/zucktown-usa-tveten
|passage=Touting its sponsorship of local engineering and sustainability programs, Amazon '''crows''' about such ‚Äúinvestments‚Äù as its dog park, playing fields, art installations, and Buckyball-reminiscent domical gardens.}}
#: {{ux|en|He's been '''crowing''' all day about winning the game of cards.}}
# To utter a sound expressive of joy or pleasure.
#* {{quote-book|lang=en|author={{w|Alfred, Lord Tennyson}}|title=The Princess|year=1847|section=Part II|passage=the sweetest little maid / That ever '''crowed''' for kisses}}
#* {{Q|en|Anthony Trollope|He Knew He Was Right|year=1868|XI|quote=The child was at this time about ten months old, and was a strong, hearty, happy infant, always laughing when he was awake and always sleeping when he did not laugh, because his little limbs were free from pain and his little stomach was not annoyed by internal troubles. He kicked, and '''crowed''', and sputtered, when his mother took him, and put up his little fingers to clutch her hair, and was to her as a young god upon the earth. Nothing in the world had ever been created so beautiful, so joyous, so satisfactory, so divine!}}
#* {{quote-book|lang=en|year=1913|author={{w|D.H. Lawrence}}|title=[[s:Sons_and_Lovers|Sons and Lovers]]|chapter=2|passage=Hearing the miner's footsteps, the baby would put up his arms and '''crow'''.}}
# {{lb|en|music}} To test the reed of a [[double reed]] instrument by placing the reed alone in the mouth and blowing it.

=====Usage notes=====
The past tense {{m|en|crew}} in modern usage is confined to literary and metaphorical uses, usually with reference to the story of Peter in ''Luke 22.60''. The past participle {{m|en|crown}} is similarly poetical.

